<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="113" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="113">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="113">
Afghanistan, Kurram valley, Sikarm, common at 3650 m., dry localities, 1879, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="113">Aitchison</emphasis>
(holotype LE!, isotype K).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="113" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="113">General distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="113">
widely distributed species, occurring from Turkey up to Bhutan and S China (
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" pagination="341 - 408" refId="B7" refString="Freitag, H, 1975. The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in southwest Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 33: 341 - 408" title="The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in southwest Asia." volume="33" year="1975">Freitag 1975</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tzvelev, NN" journalOrPublisher="Nauka, Leningrad" pageId="20" pageNumber="117" refId="B40" refString="Tzvelev, NN, 1976. Grasses of the Soviet Union. Nauka, Leningrad" title="Grasses of the Soviet Union." year="1976">Tzvelev 1976</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="113" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="113">Distribution in Nepal.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="113">
Although we did not find any specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Munro ex Nevski, Trudy Bot. Inst. Akad. Nauk SSSR Ser. 1, Fl. Sist. Vyssh. Rast. 4: 217" authorityYear="1937" baseAuthorityName="Regel" class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Piptatherum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Piptatherum laterale" order="Poales" pageId="16" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laterale">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="113">Piptatherum laterale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
during this study, it is known from nearby regions of Bhutan, China, India (
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" pagination="341 - 408" refId="B7" refString="Freitag, H, 1975. The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in southwest Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 33: 341 - 408" title="The genus Piptatherum (Gramineae) in southwest Asia." volume="33" year="1975">Freitag 1975</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Noltie, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh Journal of Botany" pageId="19" pageNumber="116" refId="B23" refString="Noltie, HJ, 2000. The Grasses of Bhutan. Flora of Bhutan, vol. 3, part. 2. Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh &amp; Royal Government of Bhutan, Edinburgh, 1-883." title="The Grasses of Bhutan. Flora of Bhutan, vol. 3, part. 2. Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh &amp; Royal Government of Bhutan, Edinburgh, 1 - 883." year="2000">Noltie 2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Wu, ZL" editor="Wu, ZY" journalOrPublisher="22. Science Press Beijing and Missouri Botanical Garden Press St. Louis" pageId="20" pageNumber="117" pagination="188 - 212" refId="B43" refString="Wu, ZL, Phillips, SM, 2006. Tribe Stipeae. In: Wu, ZY, Raven, PH, Hong, DY, Eds., Flora of China (Poaceae), vol. 22. Science Press Beijing and Missouri Botanical Garden Press St. Louis: 188 - 212" title="Tribe Stipeae." volumeTitle="Flora of China (Poaceae), vol." year="2006">Wu and Phillips 2006</bibRefCitation>
), so it is very likely also to be present in Nepal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
